>
  <p>Aptean had acquired roughly ten ERP software companies. Each had zero analytics capability and no shared infrastructure. The mandate: build one embedded analytics platform that all of them could use. I was the PM. The customers were internal product engineering teams at each acquired company — not external end-users buying a product.</p>

  <p>That distinction matters more than I treated it. Internal customers don't choose to adopt. They have to be convinced that routing through a shared layer is worth the integration cost and the loss of local control. I designed a clean API-first architecture and started building. I assumed that once the platform was good, teams would use it. They didn't. Two of the first three integrations fell apart: one team had already shipped their own solution inside their product, another wasn't going to cede control of their analytics layer regardless of how clean the shared API was.</p>

  <p>The platform eventually integrated across the portfolio. The $80M+ ARR base got consistent analytics coverage. Duplicate build work dropped significantly. But two months of rework came directly from the assumption I chose not to validate.</p>
</CaseStudy>
